<body>
<segment id="1" parent="1001" relname="preparation">Help a Suicidal Child</segment>
<segment id="2" parent="1002" relname="span">Children and adolescents may not always know how to articulate what they 're feeling inside ,</segment>
<segment id="3" parent="1003" relname="span">which means</segment>
<segment id="4" parent="1004" relname="span">they may have trouble</segment>
<segment id="5" parent="1005" relname="span">asking for help</segment>
<segment id="6" parent="5" relname="condition">when they need it .</segment>
<segment id="7" parent="1008" relname="condition">If you think a child is suicidal ,</segment>
<segment id="8" parent="1009" relname="span">the most important thing</segment>
<segment id="9" parent="8" relname="elaboration">you can do</segment>
<segment id="10" parent="1008" relname="same_unit">is to take it seriously .</segment>
<segment id="11" parent="1011" relname="span">Take precautions</segment>
<segment id="12" parent="1012" relname="joint">to keep them safe</segment>
<segment id="13" parent="1012" relname="joint">and get them professional help .</segment>
<segment id="14" parent="1015" relname="circumstance">After setting them up with a professional ,</segment>
<segment id="15" parent="1015" relname="joint">be supportive</segment>
<segment id="16" parent="1016" relname="span">and suggest constructive activities</segment>
<segment id="17" parent="16" relname="elaboration">that help them feel better .</segment>
<segment id="18" parent="1019" relname="preparation">Steps</segment>
<segment id="19" parent="1019" relname="joint">Reacting to Suicidal Behavior</segment>
<segment id="20" parent="1021" relname="preparation">Know the warning signs of suicidal behavior .</segment>
<segment id="21" parent="1024" relname="span">Most youth demonstrate some red flags in their behavior</segment>
<segment id="22" parent="21" relname="elaboration">that indicate</segment>
<segment id="23" parent="1023" relname="same_unit">they are considering suicide .</segment>
<segment id="24" parent="1021" relname="joint">A sense of hopelessness about the future</segment>
<segment id="25" parent="1026" relname="span">and comments or plans</segment>
<segment id="26" parent="25" relname="elaboration">pertaining to suicide are often clear indicators .</segment>
<segment id="27" parent="1028" relname="preparation">However , other warning signs may include :</segment>
<segment id="28" parent="1028" relname="joint">Experiencing changes in sleep or eating habits</segment>
<segment id="29" parent="1028" relname="joint">Withdrawing from friends and family ,</segment>
<segment id="30" parent="1028" relname="joint">spending more time alone</segment>
<segment id="31" parent="1028" relname="joint">Displaying acting out or angry behaviors</segment>
<segment id="32" parent="1028" relname="joint">Take threats seriously .</segment>
<segment id="33" parent="34" relname="condition">If you spot any of these warning signs in a child ,</segment>
<segment id="34" parent="1034" relname="span">take action immediately .</segment>
<segment id="35" parent="1028" relname="joint">Come straight out</segment>
<segment id="36" parent="1037" relname="span">and ask them</segment>
<segment id="37" parent="1038" relname="contrast">if they are feeling suicidal</segment>
<segment id="38" parent="1038" relname="contrast">or thinking of hurting themself .</segment>
<segment id="39" parent="1041" relname="attribution">Some people think</segment>
<segment id="40" parent="1042" relname="attribution">a child may say things like ,</segment>
<segment id="41" parent="1042" relname="contrast">" I do n't want to live anymore "</segment>
<segment id="42" parent="1043" relname="span">or " Everyone would be better off</segment>
<segment id="43" parent="1044" relname="span">if I were dead "</segment>
<segment id="44" parent="43" relname="purpose">to get attention .</segment>
<segment id="45" parent="1046" relname="span">Such threats are often cries for help from adolescents</segment>
<segment id="46" parent="1047" relname="joint">who do n't know how to cope with what they are feeling ,</segment>
<segment id="47" parent="1047" relname="joint">and these types of statements should be taken seriously .</segment>
<segment id="48" parent="1049" relname="span">Never ignore threats or warning signs</segment>
<segment id="49" parent="48" relname="elaboration">that a child is feeling suicidal .</segment>
<segment id="50" parent="1028" relname="joint">Do n't leave a suicidal child alone .</segment>
<segment id="51" parent="52" relname="condition">If you suspect a child is suicidal ,</segment>
<segment id="52" parent="1052" relname="span">stay with them .</segment>
<segment id="53" parent="1054" relname="span">Make sure that they are with someone around the clock</segment>
<segment id="54" parent="1055" relname="contrast">until the threat passes ,</segment>
<segment id="55" parent="1055" relname="contrast">or until they are able to seek professional help .</segment>
<segment id="56" parent="1028" relname="joint">Remove any weapons or drugs .</segment>
<segment id="57" parent="1058" relname="span">Check the environment for any knives , guns , narcotic medications , or anything else</segment>
<segment id="58" parent="57" relname="elaboration">that can be used as a weapon .</segment>
<segment id="59" parent="1060" relname="span">Lock these items away</segment>
<segment id="60" parent="1061" relname="span">so the child cannot use them</segment>
<segment id="61" parent="60" relname="purpose">to hurt themself .</segment>
<segment id="62" parent="1028" relname="joint">Get them to a professional as soon as possible .</segment>
<segment id="63" parent="1028" relname="joint">Most suicidal youth have an untreated psychiatric disorder such as depression .</segment>
<segment id="64" parent="1066" relname="span">Have the child seen by a professional therapist</segment>
<segment id="65" parent="64" relname="elaboration">who can help alleviate symptoms of depression</segment>
<segment id="66" parent="1028" relname="joint">and get to the root of the issue .</segment>
<segment id="67" parent="1068" relname="span">The child may require therapy and/or medications ,</segment>
<segment id="68" parent="67" relname="elaboration">depending on the underlying cause .</segment>
<segment id="69" parent="1070" relname="span">In the meantime , the therapist will likely create a safety plan for the child ,</segment>
<segment id="70" parent="1071" relname="span">which includes contact numbers and resources</segment>
<segment id="71" parent="1072" relname="span">they can access</segment>
<segment id="72" parent="71" relname="condition">if they feel suicidal .</segment>
<segment id="73" parent="1028" relname="joint">Offering Support</segment>
<segment id="74" parent="1075" relname="preparation">Encourage them to talk .</segment>
<segment id="75" parent="1076" relname="same_unit">The child may feel better</segment>
<segment id="76" parent="77" relname="condition">if they talk about the thoughts and feelings</segment>
<segment id="77" parent="1077" relname="span">they are having .</segment>
<segment id="78" parent="1079" relname="preparation">Ask ,</segment>
<segment id="79" parent="1080" relname="span">“ Do you want to talk about it ? "</segment>
<segment id="80" parent="79" relname="purpose">to encourage them to open up .</segment>
<segment id="81" parent="1082" relname="span">The child may resist your efforts</segment>
<segment id="82" parent="81" relname="purpose">to get them talking .</segment>
<segment id="83" parent="1085" relname="condition">If this happens ,</segment>
<segment id="84" parent="1086" relname="attribution">make sure</segment>
<segment id="85" parent="1087" relname="attribution">they know</segment>
<segment id="86" parent="1087" relname="span">that you are open to talk</segment>
<segment id="87" parent="86" relname="condition">whenever they feel ready .</segment>
<segment id="88" parent="1089" relname="preparation">Be an active listener .</segment>
<segment id="89" parent="90" relname="condition">If the child or adolescent wants to talk to you ,</segment>
<segment id="90" parent="1090" relname="span">practice active , non-judgemental listening .</segment>
<segment id="91" parent="1092" relname="preparation">Turn to face them ,</segment>
<segment id="92" parent="1093" relname="sequence">make eye contact ,</segment>
<segment id="93" parent="1094" relname="span">and hear what they 're saying</segment>
<segment id="94" parent="93" relname="manner">without interrupting .</segment>
<segment id="95" parent="1096" relname="contrast">Avoid saying things like " You should have ... "</segment>
<segment id="96" parent="97" relname="attribution">or " I ca n't believe</segment>
<segment id="97" parent="1097" relname="span">you would think that way . "</segment>
<segment id="98" parent="1099" relname="span">These comments can come off as judgmental and critical .</segment>
<segment id="99" parent="1100" relname="joint">Simply be there</segment>
<segment id="100" parent="1100" relname="joint">and allow them to share their feelings .</segment>
<segment id="101" parent="1092" relname="joint">Show empathy for what they 're feeling .</segment>
<segment id="102" parent="103" relname="preparation">Rather than criticizing them ,</segment>
<segment id="103" parent="1103" relname="span">be empathetic and compassionate .</segment>
<segment id="104" parent="1106" relname="attribution">Let the child know</segment>
<segment id="105" parent="1106" relname="span">that you understand</segment>
<segment id="106" parent="105" relname="elaboration">where they are coming from .</segment>
<segment id="107" parent="1109" relname="attribution">This might sound like ,</segment>
<segment id="108" parent="1110" relname="attribution">" I can see</segment>
<segment id="109" parent="1110" relname="contrast">that you have been dealing with this for a while "</segment>
<segment id="110" parent="1110" relname="contrast">or " It seems like you 've been very overwhelmed . "</segment>
<segment id="111" parent="1107" relname="joint">Attend a support group together .</segment>
<segment id="112" parent="1107" relname="joint">Help the child overcome suicidal thoughts</segment>
<segment id="113" parent="1107" relname="joint">and feel less alone in what they 're going through .</segment>
<segment id="114" parent="1116" relname="span">You can do this</segment>
<segment id="115" parent="114" relname="means">by accompanying them to a suicide support group for youth .</segment>
<segment id="116" parent="1117" relname="span">These groups offer practical strategies</segment>
<segment id="117" parent="116" relname="elaboration">for dealing with upsetting thoughts and feelings as well as support and encouragement .</segment>
<segment id="118" parent="1107" relname="joint">Ask the child 's therapist to recommend support groups in your area .</segment>
<segment id="119" parent="1107" relname="joint">Improving Their Outlook</segment>
<segment id="120" parent="1121" relname="span">Exercise with them</segment>
<segment id="121" parent="120" relname="purpose">to brighten their mood .</segment>
<segment id="122" parent="1123" relname="span">Physical activity releases feel-good chemicals</segment>
<segment id="123" parent="122" relname="elaboration">called endorphins .</segment>
<segment id="124" parent="1107" relname="joint">Endorphins can help the child feel more energetic</segment>
<segment id="125" parent="1107" relname="joint">and have a more positive outlook .</segment>
<segment id="126" parent="1107" relname="joint">Try exercising for at least 30 minutes each day .</segment>
<segment id="127" parent="1129" relname="preparation">By exercising with them ,</segment>
<segment id="128" parent="1129" relname="joint">you 'll help them engage socially</segment>
<segment id="129" parent="1129" relname="joint">and make sure they are doing something good for their bodies .</segment>
<segment id="130" parent="1131" relname="span">Consider going for a walk around the neighborhood ,</segment>
<segment id="131" parent="1132" relname="contrast">shooting hoops ,</segment>
<segment id="132" parent="1132" relname="contrast">or going for a swim .</segment>
<segment id="133" parent="1134" relname="span">Encourage them to spend time</segment>
<segment id="134" parent="1135" relname="span">doing things</segment>
<segment id="135" parent="134" relname="elaboration">they enjoy .</segment>
<segment id="136" parent="1107" relname="joint">Drive a budding photographer to a beautiful landscape for pictures .</segment>
<segment id="137" parent="1138" relname="span">Purchase lessons for a child</segment>
<segment id="138" parent="137" relname="elaboration">who is interested in guitar or piano .</segment>
<segment id="139" parent="1107" relname="joint">Hobbies and passions can help the child feel better about life</segment>
<segment id="140" parent="1141" relname="span">and remember things</segment>
<segment id="141" parent="140" relname="elaboration">they are good at .</segment>
<segment id="142" parent="1144" relname="span">Work with them</segment>
<segment id="143" parent="142" relname="purpose">to pare down their responsibilities .</segment>
<segment id="144" parent="1145" relname="span">The child may be stressed out due to demanding school work and extracurricular activities .</segment>
<segment id="145" parent="1146" relname="span">Sit down with them</segment>
<segment id="146" parent="145" relname="elaboration">and look at their schedule .</segment>
<segment id="147" parent="1107" relname="joint">Are they over-committing ?</segment>
<segment id="148" parent="1150" relname="condition">If so ,</segment>
<segment id="149" parent="1150" relname="span">help them trim down their weekly routine</segment>
<segment id="150" parent="149" relname="purpose">so that they have a more balanced , realistic schedule .</segment>
<segment id="151" parent="1107" relname="joint">Encourage social activities over solo ones .</segment>
<segment id="152" parent="1107" relname="joint">Suicidal children may be more likely to pull away from others</segment>
<segment id="153" parent="1107" relname="joint">and spend time alone .</segment>
<segment id="154" parent="1107" relname="joint">Stress the importance of social engagement</segment>
<segment id="155" parent="1107" relname="joint">and provide opportunities for them to spend time with friends and family .</segment>
<segment id="156" parent="1107" relname="joint">Host a BBQ</segment>
<segment id="157" parent="1107" relname="joint">and invite kids from school or the neighborhood ,</segment>
<segment id="158" parent="1107" relname="joint">or plan a family movie or game night .</segment>
<segment id="159" parent="1159" relname="span">You might also encourage the child to join new clubs or organizations at school</segment>
<segment id="160" parent="159" relname="purpose">so they can make new friends .</segment>
<segment id="161" parent="1161" relname="preparation">Warnings</segment>
<segment id="162" parent="1163" relname="span">While there are things</segment>
<segment id="163" parent="1164" relname="span">you can do</segment>
<segment id="164" parent="163" relname="purpose">to help and support your child ,</segment>
<segment id="165" parent="166" relname="attribution">remember</segment>
<segment id="166" parent="1165" relname="span">that nobody can entirely prevent suicide .</segment>
<segment id="167" parent="1161" relname="joint">You cannot control your child ’s thoughts or actions .</segment>
<segment id="168" parent="1161" relname="joint">What you can do</segment>
<segment id="169" parent="1161" relname="joint">is be supportive and encouraging ,</segment>
<segment id="170" parent="1169" relname="span">give them the help and resources</segment>
<segment id="171" parent="1171" relname="span">they need</segment>
<segment id="172" parent="171" relname="purpose">to get better ,</segment>
<segment id="173" parent="174" relname="attribution">and let them know</segment>
<segment id="174" parent="1172" relname="span">that you are there for them .</segment>
